"Cheng T.H., Gu X.F., Chen L.F., Yu T., Tian G.L.","Multiangular polarized characteristics of optically thin cirrus in the visible and near-infrared spectral region",2010,"Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences","67","3",,"749","768",,,10.1175/2009JAS2996.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77953344203&partnerID=40&md5=086e5507cbd55c52aad1412fec75f513","State Key Laboratory of Remote Sensing Science, Beijing, China","Cheng, T.H., State Key Laboratory of Remote Sensing Science, Beijing, China; Gu, X.F., State Key Laboratory of Remote Sensing Science, Beijing, China; Chen, L.F., State Key Laboratory of Remote Sensing Science, Beijing, China; Yu, T., State Key Laboratory of Remote Sensing Science, Beijing, China; Tian, G.L., State Key Laboratory of Remote Sensing Science, Beijing, China","Optically thin cirrus play a key role in the earth's radiation budget and global climate change. Their radiative effects depend critically on the thin cirrus optical and microphysical properties. In this paper, in-homogeneous hexagonal monocrystals (IHMs), which consist of a pure hexagon with spherical air bubble or aerosol inclusions, are applied to calculate the single-scattering properties of individual ice crystals. The multiangular polarized characteristics of optically thin cirrus for the 0.865-and 1.38-μm spectral bands are simulated on the basis of an adding-doubling radiative transfer program. The sensitivity of total and polarized reflectance at the top of the atmosphere (TOA) to different aerosol, cirrus, and surface parameters is studied. A new sensitivity index is introduced to further quantify the sensitivity study. The TOA polarized reflectance measured by the Polarization and Directionality of the Earth's Reflectance (POLDER) instruments is compared to simulated TOA total and polarized reflectance. The test results are reasonable, although small deviations caused by the change of aerosol properties and thin cirrus optical thickness do exist. Finally, on the basis of the sensitivity study, a conceptual approach is suggested to simultaneously retrieve thin cirrus clouds' optical thickness, ice particle shape, and the underlying aerosol optical thickness using the TOA total and polarized reflectance of the 0.865-and 1.38-μm spectral bands measured at multiple viewing angles. © 2010 American Meteorological Society.",,"Aerosol optical thickness; Aerosol properties; Air bubbles; Global climate changes; Ice crystals; Ice particles; Microphysical property; Mono-crystals; Optical thickness; Polarized reflectances; Radiation budget; Radiative effects; Sensitivity indices; Sensitivity studies; Single scattering; Spectral band; Surface parameter; Test results; Thin cirrus; Top of the atmospheres; Viewing angle; Visible and near infrared; Atmospheric aerosols; Climate change; Earth (planet); Optical properties; Reflection; Clouds; aerosol; cirrus; climate change; cloud microphysics; global climate; ice crystal; near infrared; POLDER; radiation budget; radiative transfer; sensitivity analysis; top of atmosphere",,,,,,"Baum, B.A., Soulen, P.F., Strabala, K.I., King, M.D., Ackerman, S.A., Menzel, W.P., Yang, P., Remote sensing of cloud properties using MODIS Airborne Simulator imagery during SUCCESS 2. Cloud thermodynamic phase (2000) Geophys. Res., 105, pp. 11 781-11 792; Baum, B.A., Heymsfield, A.J., Yang, P., Bedka, S.T., Bulk scattering properties for the remote sensing of ice clouds. Part I: Microphysical data and models (2005) J. Appl. Meteor., 44, pp. 1885-1895; Baum, B.A., Yang, P., Heymsfield, A.J., Platnick, S., King, M.D., Hu, Y.-X., Bedka, S.T., Bulk scattering properties for the remote sensing of ice clouds. Part II: Narrowband models (2005) J. Appl. Meteor., 44, pp. 1896-1911; Baum, B.A., Yang, P., Nasiri, S.L., Heidinger, A.K., Heymsfield, A.J., Li, J., Bulk scattering properties for the remote sensing of ice clouds. Part III: High-resolution spectral models from 100 to 3250 cm-1 (2007) J. Appl. Meteor. Climatol., 4